>
> On Friday 16 April 2004 17:39, you wrote:
> > Hi Shlomi,
> >
> >     Don't know if you may have already replied to my earlier message, as
> > for some hopefully temporary reason, I was not able to recover E-mail
> > just now.
> >
> >     But I did have a chance to get my son's slant on the question of
> > voluntary social security, so thought I'd report this.
>
> Well, I think we can ask two questions about social security:
>
> 1. Is it voluntary?
>
> 2. Is it beneficial?
>
> I think we can agree that in its current state-sponsored form it is
> involuntary. Now, we can ask if in its current form, it is actually "good",
> or whether a voluntary replacement (such as private companies offering
> social security services), would be better.
>
> I cannot immediately rule out the possibility that it is bad just because
> it is involuntary. Many libertarians believe in the meta-argument that
> every government service or requirement should be voluntary, or else "one
> puts a gun against one's head and tells him to share". (to quote Eric S.
> Raymond from "Revolution OS".)
>
> I believe that it is ethically illegal to force people to give away their
> money (or other resources) to causes that they do not voluntarily agree to.
> But you may wish to reject this claim, as your credo is different than
> mine.
>
> >     His first reaction is that social security has proven to be the most
> > successful anti-poverty program ever devised, and has worked extremely
> > well. Before it was introduced, large numbers of elderly people lived in
> > poverty, and if they could not be supported by their children, became
> > wards of the state.
>
> Well, I define anti-poverty activity, not as the state supporting people,
> but as making the people be able to support themselves. This argument is
> relatively void as far as old age is concerned, as many people cannot
> support themselves during their old age, due to the deteriorating
> conditions of their body.
>
> What Neo-Tech has to say about it is that a person needs to make sure he
> can somehow support himself in his old age, without help from the
> government. (which cannot be really trusted). A long-term solution is
> proposed by the development of youth-rejuvanating biological immortality.
> This is as far as we know, impossible with the state of the art, but may be
> developed in the future. (especially with better socio-economical
> conditions that those prevalent today). This is still mostly a pipe-dream,
> however.
>
> > It is widely believed that if it were made voluntary even
> > today, many young people would foolishly opt out of it, and would meet
> > financial disaster late in their lives.
>
> Possibly. The question is whether the right thing to do would be to try and
> prevent it. After all, a man also has a right to act foolishly, and harm
> himself. I agree that it isn't desirable that it would happen, though.
>
> > The problem is exacerbated by the
> > fact that rightwing politicians are constatntly raising storm signals and
> > making accusations that the system is not fundamentally sound and could
> > go bankrupt.
>
> I read in a booklet called "The Capitalistic Manifesto" that my father
> received in one of his mailing lists, that the American National Debt is
> actually over twice (or maybe even three times, can't remember) its
> registered amount if we take social security (or something else similar)
> into account. This booklet had other interesting musings, but I did not
> thoroughly read it. (maybe we still have it somewhere).
>
> > That is false alarmism, and while the system in the US may need
> > some adjustment, it can easily be fixed (the same does not necessarily
> > apply to the medical support system -- that's another problem, and of
> > much more serious import).
>
> I'm not sure how easily it can be fixed. Government services, can often go
> from good to worse very easily. Just look at the public education system in
> the U.S. or in Israel.
>
> > I'd add on my own that if it were made voluntary,
> > there would no doubt spring up a whole new industry of private financial
> > services that would offer alternatives to social security, and some of
> > these would inevitably be poorly (even if honestly) managed, and leave
> > many people destitute in old age.  Some could well be simply dishonest
> > and steal the people's money.
>
> Well, I'm not sure if it is better to put all the eggs in one basket. It
> may be in this case, but I'm not sure.
>
> > So a compulsory system is simply best and is the only
> > way to avoid these pitfalls.  In the US, this is tacitlly acknowledged
> > even by the most conservative of economists and politicians.  We
> > sometimes have advocacy to introduce some partially-voluntary variations
> > to the system, but no one ever proposes making it fully voluntary.
>
> What you say does seem to "make sense" on the surface. I'm not sure if I
> know what arguments do objectivists and libertarians have to say about it,
> but I did raise some doubts. (at least I hope I did).
>
> In any case, I don't find this thread of discussion (regarding Social
> Security) particularly interesting.
>
> Regards,
>
> 	Shlomi Fish

